<br>
We are at war.  Not just America, but Britain and Australia, too. Other countries support us, others do not.  There is no turning back now, there is nothing further debate and name calling can do to take back the action.  Get your panties in a twist if it'll make you feel better, but keep things in perspective, please.<br>
<br>
We cannot let anti-war sentiments (no matter how valid they may be) interfere with our support of the troops who are over there putting their lives on the line.  We should make damn sure that our political views do not escalate to the point where we stop hating the war and start hating the men and women fighting it. Our defence force personnel had 4/5 of fuck all to do with the decision of whether to or not to go to war. Remember that!<br>
<br>
I guarantee you that a percentage of those overseas fighting right now do not want to be there. They may not even agree with the fact that we're there at all.  But what they ARE doing is their very best under the most trying and terrifying of circumstances. Try motivating yourself to go to work when you hate your job... now think about motivating yourself to go to work when you hate the job you've been asked to do and your country is telling you the job sucks and in the middle of all that, doing the job could get you killed.  Not fun, I would think.<br>
<br>
The war is one thing but let's not mix up politics and religion and fanaticism with the young men and women who are being shot at RIGHT NOW!  On both sides of the fight.<br>
<br>
Hate the war if you want, disagree with being there if you want, that's your right, but let's not turn this into another Vietnam where our soldiers are spat on and ridiculed for fighting in our name.<br>
<br>
That will be the real test.  Can we disagree with something and respect and support the ones on the front line simultanously?  I'd like to think we can.<br>
